<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOP AIR POLLUTION PENALTIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The South Coast Air Quality Management District has responsibility to control 
air pollution. It can seek court-imposed fines against polluters of $25 to 
$25,000 a day based on such factors as the extent that emissions exceed legal 
limits, potential danger to the public, whether the violation was intentional, 
accidental or caused by negligence and the company's history of 
violations.These are the four companies that incurred violations resulting in 
penalites of $2,500 or greater in July: COMPANY: Ultramar Inc., Wilmington TYPE 
OF BUSINESS: Refinery PENALTY: $18,500 VIOLATION: Excessive visible and gaseous 
volatile organic compund emissions, improper use of air pollution control 
equipment contrary to permit conditions. * 
</P>
<P>
 COMPANY: Smith Barney/Shearson Lehman, Los Angeles TYPE OF BUSINESS: Stock 
brokerage firm PENALTY: $10,000 VIOLATION: Failure to implement the compressed 
work week incentive outlined in its ride-sharing plan, failure to submit a 
biennial ride-sharing plan, failure to implement other incentives in its 
AQMD-approved plan. The firm will spend an additional $10,000 to add cash 
incentives to its ride-sharing plan and to use posters, flyers and other 
promotional materials to encourage ride-sharing. * 
</P>
<P>
 COMPANY: Inland Container Corp., Ontario TYPE OF BUSINESS: Paper mill PENALTY: 
$5,000 VIOLATION: Operating a co-generation system contrary to permit 
conditions. * 
</P>
<P>
 COMPANY: Coltec Industries, Menasco Overahaul Division, Burbank TYPE OF 
BUSINESS: Aircraft landing gear maker PENALTY: $4,000 VIOLATION: Operating 
equipment with expired and/or inactive permits, using unapproved equipment. The 
company will spend an additional $5,000 to purchase a newer, more efficient 
degreaser. 
</P>
</TEXT>
