<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: DOWNTOWN LOS ANGELES; 
PROTESTERS CALL FOR LAPD REINSTATEMENT OF PARKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Several dozen protesters demonstrated outside Los Angeles police headquarters 
Tuesday, calling for the reinstatement of Assistant Chief Bernard C. Parks to 
the No. 2 spot in the LAPD, a job that Chief Willie L. Williams has moved to 
strip from his top aide. 
</P>
<P>
 "We feel that management has done an injustice," said Herbert Andrew, one of 
those who gathered outside the headquarters carrying signs saying "Parks: We 
Support You." 
</P>
<P>
 Several of the demonstrators angrily denounced Williams, who said last week he 
was demoting Parks and restructuring his management team to propel the 
department toward change. Since then, the demotion and the restructuring have 
stirred the most contentious political debate of Williams' tenure. 
</P>
<P>
 The demonstrators had hoped to address the Police Commission, but that group's 
weekly meeting was canceled because commissioners could not muster a quorum. 
Meanwhile, Parks was granted a 30-day extension of a deadline to decide whether 
to accept a demotion or a deal under which he would be allowed to retire at his 
current rank in February, when he will mark his 30th year with the LAPD. 
</P>
<P>
 In return for being allowed to retire at his highest rank and pay, Parks would 
have to agree not to sue the city, the mayor or Chief Williams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
