<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIMPSON TEAM SUBPOENAS PROSECUTORS FOR PRETRIAL HEARING; COURT: DEFENSE HOPES 
TO SOLICIT TESTIMONY ABOUT POLICE SEARCHES. CLARK, HODGMAN ARE EXPECTED TO 
FIGHT THE MOVE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANDREA FORD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Prosecutors in the O.J. Simpson double-murder case could find themselves on 
the witness stand if his lawyers win a bid to solicit testimony at a pretrial 
hearing scheduled to begin today.  
</P>
<P>
 Defense lawyers have subpoenaed Deputy Dist. Attys. Marcia Clark and Bill 
Hodgman in an attempt to force them to testify about what went on during police 
searches conducted in their presence. 
</P>
<P>
 David Conn, a third prosecutor who worked on the case early on but who has 
since been reassigned, also has been subpoenaed. 
</P>
<P>
 Simpson has pleaded not guilty in the June 12 slayings of his ex-wife, Nicole 
Brown Simpson, and a friend, Ronald Lyle Goldman. Jury selection in his trial 
is scheduled to begin next week. 
</P>
<P>
 Defense attorneys hope to use the prosecutors' testimony to prove that 
evidence taken from Simpson's home, vehicles and business office should be 
thrown out because of alleged police improprieties. 
</P>
<P>
 Clark and Hodgman are expected to vehemently argue that no witnesses should be 
called at the hearing because much of the issue was covered during Simpson's 
preliminary hearing. They also will oppose the motion to suppress the evidence. 
</P>
<P>
 Among about 20 witnesses the defense wants to call are Los Angeles Police 
Detective Mark Fuhrman, who testified in an earlier proceeding that he found 
one of the key pieces of evidence against Simpson at the former football star's 
estate -- a bloodied glove similar to one found near the bodies. 
</P>
<P>
 Clark has called the glove part of a "bloody trail" Simpson left behind after 
the slayings, a trail that she contends also included droplets of blood found 
at the murder scene, on a Ford Bronco owned by Simpson and at his estate. 
</P>
<P>
 Defense lawyers have attacked the integrity of the evidence, contending that 
it was either illegally obtained or tainted by sloppy handling. They have 
suggested that Fuhrman planted the glove on Simpson's property, though no 
evidence of that has been offered. 
</P>
<P>
 Fuhrman's lawyers have scheduled a news conference today, where they are 
expected to try to discredit a woman who has given the defense a sworn 
affidavit questioning the detective's character and objectivity toward Simpson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
