<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUFFINGTON GETS PERSONAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Republican U.S. Senate challenger Mike Huffington released two new television 
commercials recently that are on the air statewide. The ads make no mention of 
his Democratic opponent, Sen. Dianne Feinstein. 
</P>
<P>
 * THE HUFFINGTON ADS: The 60-second version of Huffington's ad begins with 
video from several of California's natural disasters -- the Malibu fire, the 
Northridge earthquake and floods. A narrator's voice says: "The recent years 
have tested the will of the men and women who make California great -- the 
ranchers, the farmers, the teachers, the factory workers and small business 
owners. And while nearly 1 million people packed up and moved away, Mike 
Huffington and his wife came back to the state that educated him and is the 
birthplace of their two daughters." Huffington is then pictured, speaking to 
the camera about a need for "new solutions to old problems." A narrator says 
Huffington voted against tax increases and then Huffington speaks to the 
camera: "It was easy. The government didn't earn that money, the people did." 
The commercial ends with the line: "This election isn't just about who you'll 
send to Washington next year, it's about our children and their future." The 
30-second version of the ad contains the same message with some elements 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
 * THE ANALYSIS: Polls show that more than half of the state's voters say they 
do not know much about Huffington. As a result, his campaign hopes to introduce 
the candidate and his family as well as to establish his connections to 
California and his recognition of the state's problems. Part of the commercial 
seeks to counter the criticism that Huffington does not understand California 
because he moved to the state in 1991. The ad refers to Huffington's previous 
residence in California when he attended Stanford University. Huffington has 
also campaigned against higher taxes, noting that he opposed President 
Clinton's 1993 economic package which included a higher levy on upper-income 
individuals and Social Security recipients as well as a general gasoline tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
